For further reading: Destin Jenkins (
@DestinKJenkins
) has also written brilliantly about the fraught history of cities attempting to use bond markets to invest in vulnerable communities, and the need for Black organizers to have a seat at the table.What Does It Really Mean to Invest In Black Communities?
As the call grows to “divest and invest,” it is essential that we not exchange the violence of the police for the violence of finance capitalism.
thenation.com

Our campaign is proud to have signed the 
@NoFossilMoney
 pledge.

We stand with the #NoDrillingWhereWereLiving Campaign, 
@SunriseMvmtLA
, and 
@STAND_LA
 in their efforts to fight back against environmental racism.

Replying to 
@nithyavramanEven old, inactive wells pose major risks. And because drilling has occurred in LA for over 100 years, many companies come and go leaving dangerous wells behind.

800 oil companies have dissolved with no plans to seal or clean their former wells.

UPDATE: 
@boreskes
 with 
@latimes
 reports that the city has reversed its decision and the Pan-Pacific Park emergency shelter is staying open. Thank you for voicing your opposition! We need all the services and shelter we can get right now.

Replying to 
@nithyavramanAt 73 beds, Pan-Pacific Park is LA's 3rd-largest emergency shelter, and the only one for miles. Some people staying there will move to a Westwood shelter, but many will be back on the street.

Closing it now is an act of cruelty. And we haven’t even been told why it’s happening.

Replying to 
@nithyavramanThe backlog at DFEH is also a big problem in LA’s entertainment industry, where jobs are often short term and LLCs are created on a project-by-project basis.

By the time the state weighs in, the job is often finished, and liability is limited to that specific project.

Replying to 
@nithyavramanAs far back as 1988, LA Mayor Tom Bradley called for a ban of styrofoam takeout containers. Many of LA’s neighbors have passed such bans, including Pasadena, Santa Monica, Long Beach, Manhattan Beach, and Hermosa Beach.

LA has explored styrofoam bans but taken no action. Why?

Replying to 
@nithyavramanWage theft enforcement is complicated: workers are often afraid to speak up, due to immigration status or fear of retribution.

But the Investigation and Compliance Section of LA’s Office of Wage Standards mostly works by reacting to complaints. What about unreported violations?

Replying to 
@nithyavramanSweeps also result in unhoused people’s possessions getting thrown out, including tents, medication, and ID documents like birth certificates.

These documents are necessary for accessing services. Losing them in sweeps can prevent individuals from getting housing or treatment.

Replying to 
@nithyavramanHHH isn’t the only recent supportive housing push that came up short. In 2018, every councilmember pledged to approve 222 units by 7/1/2020.

Even though 222 units per district is far short of what we need, six councilmembers didn't even meet that goal.

Los Feliz/Thai Town residents! My Friend’s Place (
@MFPLA
) does amazing work providing services to unhoused and at-risk youth, offering meals, clothing, medical care, referrals to case management, mental health care, transformative educational programs, and housing assistance.

Live in Silver Lake? Donate blood tomorrow! The Silverlake Independent Jewish Community Center (
@eastsidejews
) is hosting a socially-distant blood drive in their parking lot.

They also offer online programming during COVID-19. Check out their calendar:SIJCC Events Calendar — SIJCC
sijcc.net

Replying to 
@nithyavramanKtown folks! Koreatown Youth + Community Center (
@KYCCLA
) has been an incredible resource since 1975, engaging in economic development, clinical services, mental health counseling, drug treatment, tax prep, childcare services, and so much more.

Replying to 
@nithyavramanUnlicensed vendors who have kept operating have been targeted by law enforcement and fined between $200 and $1000.

At the same time, health inspectors found that 83% of bars and restaurants weren’t following COVID-19 guidelines. No fines were issued.

Replying to 
@nithyavramanThere are many public broadband networks that LA could model after -- an oft-cited success story is Chattanooga. 

They built their own high-speed network, and residents now get online at a gig/second: more than 2x as fast as a similarly-priced plan in LA.

Replying to 
@nithyavramanOur lack of data about rental properties makes it nearly impossible to enforce tenant rights -- which are being violated right now.

Last month the LAT found evidence of 290 illegal evictions in the pandemic's first 10 weeks, mostly in South LA.

Excited to be featured in this brilliant piece by 
@PiperSFrench
 alongside 
@fatima4assembly
, whose values-driven campaign inspires me so much. Follow her and get involved!Piper French
@PiperSFrench
 · Jul 13
i wrote about the LA county political establishment, in which every politician is “progressive” but cops run the show & unhoused residents are routinely terrorized - and two incredible first-time candidates who are calling bullshit on these contradictions. https://currentaffairs.org/2020/07/taking-on-the-l-a-political-establishment…
